<h2>Event in December 2020</h2>
The first days of December 2020 were characterized by large amounts of rain in Northern Italy and the western coast of the Balkan countries (see Figure 9 depicting the highest 1-day and 5-day precipitation amounts). Heavy downpours lead to river flooding of the Secchia, one of the tributaries of the Po river, and to flooding streets in Modena (Emilia-Romagna). A storm surge caused by strong winds over the Adriatic Sea also led to flooding of the streets and squares of Venice, and more inland the concurrent heavy precipitation led to flooding in the city of Vicenza. On the 7th of December Trieste and surroundings were hit by an intense isolated storm with hail, high wind speeds, lightning and heavy precipitation.
<br><br>
Figure 1 illustrates the situation during these exceptional events on 5 and 6 December. Low pressure occurred over the UK and North Sea, extending southward over the the Gulf of Biscay and France. Combined with the large high pressure area over Russia this resulted in a southerly flow over Italy and surrounding Mediterranean Sea, transporting warm and humid air northward. During the second part of December a significantly calmer situation prevailed over the area.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/dec2020/5and6Dec-PrecWind.png"><img alt="" src="../images/dec2020/5and6Dec-PrecWind.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1. Daily precipitation from E-OBS and surface windfield at 12 UTC from ERA5 on 5 (Upper figure) and 6 (Lower figure) December 2020, indicating the strong convergence of warm and humid air to Northern Italy.</em>
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for December 2020</h2>
<br><br>
As December was relatively warm almost everywhere in Europe (figures 4 and 5), the heating degree days were less than average (figure 1, right panel). The heating degree days are defined as the sum over the days of (17 &deg;C - TG), where TG is the daily mean temperature, and the sum is done only over the days with TG less than 17 &deg;C. The heating degree days anomaly was particularly negative in Scandinavia, although the heating degree days themselves in this cold region were still high (figure 2, left panel).
